Interviewer: Could you briefly summarise your experience choosing your courses for the very first time back in first year? 
Participant: Yeah so in first year I mostly just relied on the recommended course list that UQ puts out. There's like a guide that breaks it down by program, so I just followed that. For goal courses I kind of just picked whatever looked interesting and fit my timetable. 
Interviewer: And how did that go for you? Any issues? 
Participant: I accidentally enrolled in a second-year course in my first sem. Didn't realise until like week two and had to drop it — it messed up my schedule a bit, which was pretty annoying. 
Interviewer: Which parts of the course selection process did you find most challenging? 
Participant: The course codes threw me off at first. I didn't know how to tell which year level a course was without actually clicking into it, and some of the prerequisite info was buried. You'd only find out you couldn't enrol after you'd already tried. 
Interviewer: In what ways did the organisation of information across UQ's web pages impact your experience? 
Participant: The my.UQ site and the course profiles felt kind of separate from each other. Like I'd be in SI-net trying to add a course but then have to go to a completely different page to check if it was the right one. It wasn't hard exactly, just kind of scattered. 
Interviewer: Was it easy to find and understand information about course difficulty, workload, or assessments? 
Participant: Not really, to be honest. The course profiles give you the official description but that doesn't tell you much about what it's actually like. I ended up asking people on Discord — like the UQ student servers — way more than I used the official pages. Past students are way more useful. 
Interviewer: So who or what did you mostly rely on when making your choices? 
Participant: Definitely friends and Discord. The UQ website was more like a starting point to get the course name and code, and then I'd go find real information from people who'd actually done it. 
Interviewer: If the enrolment system had some kind of built-in guidance, what form would have been most helpful? 
